USA: Repetition is mother of wisdom
He even becomes a comedian, the stubborn effort with which Barack Obama, president of the reputation of sage, reproduces the strategy of his predecessor on the Afghan question, which he himself considered to be quite simple.
When he finally let his doctrine so eagerly awaited, it turned out that he had copied it on carbon paper since Bush’s Iraqi scenario three years ago.
Not content with using the phrase “as in Iraq” several times in the text, he did not hesitate to use the title of Bush’s January 2007 speech as the title of his own speech: “A New Road Forward.”
At the same time, he personally criticized Bush’s idea of sending new reinforcements into a war-torn Iraq as being “irresponsible and a catastrophic decision in its aftermath.”
The following months, however, showed that Bush's strategy, which emanated from the recommendations of the campaign commanders, was the only possible and likely to succeed to such an extent that the newspapers at present do not speak at all about Iraq.
This did not improve Bush’s reputation, that is, objectively speaking, it left his successor with a much more favourable final situation than could be hoped for.
Barack Obama hopes that in Afghanistan, the miracle will happen again
Again, it was the campaign commanders who asked for an increase in the military contingent, including the commander of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even severely criticized the White House's reluctance despite subordination habits.
He asked for 40,000 men to make the situation more favourable.
The president hesitated for three months but in the absence of a better option, he at least swindled the 10,000-strong general.
He succeeded in extracting the promise of an additional 5,000 from Europe, even though he originally counted on 10,000.
What brings the most problems to Obama’s entire strategy seems to be his intention to withdraw the armies from Afghanistan in 18 months and to complete this whole process in three years. Obama’s whole doctrine brings more questions than it provides answers.
Many doubt that a halved increase will bring the same results as progress in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized and its leaders honor the agreements.
The Afghan situation is marked by the exact opposite - no one can be counted on and no treaty is respected.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, accustomed to changing leadership day by day according to what arranges them.
Political institutions, although officially founded, will remain only a powder in the eyes behind which patriarchal ethnic relations will proliferate.
It is singularly complex to balance the interests of the various ethnic groups given the lack of clarity about the reports, which are still complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the foundation of a “prompt state to act”, which is the basic purpose of the operation, does not seem to be very real.
The time horizon of Obama’s strategy is puzzling by his voluntarism.
In the last eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is currently on the brink of chaos.
Only a purely romantic and out-of-reality heart can be persuaded that the small soldiers sent into the tumult of war for their "immediate return home" will bring there a real miracle.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible since the Taliban will regard it as an indirect admission of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit has shown that the willingness of Europeans to participate in military operations in Afghanistan is heading towards the negative.
European politicians do not know or want to explain to their voters how security in Germany or Italy is linked to a war in the mountains of the Hindu Kush.
Another factor capable of radically altering the situation is the evolution of events related to Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the Americans will find themselves faced with the very difficult question of a solution to the problem through the use of military force.
We will have to respond, for example, when, according to Obama, America will come to the victorious withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
Each solution of this kind will, however, result in a dramatic reversal of the Afghan situation.
The only downside for Obama is the fact that there are three years left until the presidential election and therefore there is still enough time left for him to work on a new strategy, in case it turns out to be a total fiasco.
