Czech discovery: a substance that works on "endurable" HIV viruses too
A team of Czech and German scientists are testing new combinations that can slow the spread of the HIV virus in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also acts on viruses that have already developed immunity to drugs.
This reality, in some cases, takes precedence over the fact that the combination does not act as intensely on common variants of the virus as well as certain drugs already available.
It is not possible to cure AIDS at this time.
Nevertheless, the life of patients can be radically extended through a mixture of drugs that prevent the HIV virus from multiplying in the body.
However, their consumption results in a number of side effects.
In addition, the suppression of this multiplication has the effect of developing what are called resistant viruses on which the drugs no longer have effect.
The work of experts from three institutions, the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the V<0xC5><0xA0>CHT in Prague and the University of Heidelberg paves the way for a way to deal with the resistance of the virus.
They showed that substances called metallocarbons act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metallocarbons are an assembly of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a different way from all the drugs used so far and that is why they could overcome the problem of resistance.
The work of the researchers leads them to discover new "improved" substances, based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their connections to virus proteins.
Metallocarbons have a unique three-dimensional structure: two cages with multiple walls are formed by the atoms of boron, hydrogen and carbon and connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
A traitorous and resistant virus.
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential to the life cycle of the virus.
Without the division of the HIV virus caused by the HIV protease, there would be no birth of mature infectious particles of the virus.
If HIV protease is stopped, the spread of the virus will also be stopped in the patient's body, the researchers said in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In their work published in the scientific journal Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of combinations in which two pairs of cages (see table) are connected by a short organic chain, which is then systematically modified.
A little weaker but more reliable.
The efficacy of this series of substances on HIV proteases has been tested in trials as well as on its resistant variants, obtained from HIV-infected patients.
On the current version of the enzyme, the effect of metallocarbons is not as strong as on clinical drugs, however, it does not weaken on the resistant versions against which the current drugs are often ineffective.
Metallocarbons, with their unique mechanism of action and their other properties such as their biological and chemical stability, their low toxicity and the possibility of other chemical modifications, are therefore interesting combinations to consider further in order to move towards the development of effective drugs against HIV, says Pavl<0xC3><0xAD>na <0xC5><0x98>ez<0xC3><0xA1><0xC4><0x8D>ov<0xC3><0xA1>, Director of the Laboratory of Organic Biology and the Director of the Laboratory of Organic Chemistry.
