The managerial revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of large French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been in vain.
For more than a decade, the attitude of the management of large companies vis-<0xC3><0xA0>-vis its employees, recalls the position of companies vis-<0xC3><0xA0>-vis consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about making employees adhere to determined "values" from above as it used to be, to impose on consumers products thought through technology.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has put the strategies of conquering markets in place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose disconnected products from customer preference factors returns regularly!
A demobilization of employees can lead to a deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the emerging part of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, including R&D and, even more, economic intelligence.
Indeed, the EI "requires all stakeholders ... a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision"; it requires from employees a commitment that the revenues of authoritarian management totally contradict.
That is why we call for a managerial revolution that would be to put employees at the center of the company's concerns as well as the customer.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion polls
Will internal opinion polls – such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – incite this revolution in managerial practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- First, because I have been able to see that, in the face of a new situation, any structure finally comes to do, after many detours, as a priority... what it has always done.
- Then, because authoritarianism – one of the pathologies of power – grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
Coming from the major engineering schools, they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, by intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the American "neurosciences" and widely disseminated, without their knowledge, by the institutes of studies and the media.
Thus, suggesting that it is possible to handle the "leverages" (sic) of the commitment of executives, a recent survey of Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr strengthens the leaders in a position of mechanistic governance, unsuitable for today's world.
Identifying and Measuring Mobilization Factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises presupposes adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists in integrating, in any reasoning or practice of governance, a fundamental statement: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a way to realize some of their dreams, ambitions, projects.
Currently, only studies from the Motif Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to realize their life projects.
By identifying and measuring these mobilization factors, business leaders can control, predict and anticipate their “social performance” and put their human resource management “in place.”
They thus create a terrain conducive to the concerted development of robust and efficient economic intelligence.
Oslo Speech: ‘Just War’ Worth Praises Right to Obama
The American right welcomed the speech delivered in Oslo the day before by Barack Obama, satisfied that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize defended the concept of “just war” against the enemies of the United States.
