The Cradle of Dinosaurs
The Tawa hallae resembled other carnivorous dinosaurs: this biped was about 2 meters long by 1.50 meters high, its hind limbs were powerful, its elongated skull was provided with sharp and curved teeth, its short arms ended with sickle claws and it had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would have had nothing exceptional.
But, as Sertling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in Thursday’s Science magazine report, the Tawa hallae is one of the first dinosaurs to feature these morphological features.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico which was then part of the emerging lands of the supercontinent, the Pangea and was located towards the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says that the discovery of the Tawa sheds new light on the evolution of the first dinosaurs.
Indeed, it informs us about the kinship links, the distribution and the characteristics of the latter.
It was in 2006 that Sertling Nesbitt undertook excavations with other paleontologists at the Gohst Ranch site in northern New Mexico.
Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History and a member of the excavation team says that they sometimes found a dozen bones in a day, which is absolutely unique for a sedimentary layer dating back to the Trias.
Scientists soon realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
The excavations have updated the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms the theories concerning the beginnings of the evolution of dinosaurs.
The researchers named it Tawa after the Hopi word for the sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is a truly exceptional discovery: dinosaur fossils from the Trias are extremely rare and are limited to a few incomplete bone fragments.
Not all paleontology experts share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not think that this discovery is particularly spectacular, but he points out that it allows to confirm some theories regarding the beginnings of the evolution of dinosaurs.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
Most of the oldest fossils, however, are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify the very first dinosaurs.
Experts wonder, among other things, at what time the saurians were divided into three major groups of evolution: the theropods (carnivores) which include the later tyrannosaur and the velociraptor and from which descend the birds, sauropods, quadrupeds at the long neck, and those which are related to them and the herbivores.
According to the studies of S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, the Tawa is one of the first theropods.
This species has an interesting relationship of both primitive and developed characteristics, says S. Nesbitt.
The researchers found clues that suggest the Tawa hallae possessed small air sacs in its skull-level bones, as did the birds that are the descendants of the theropods.
These small air pockets make it easier for birds to breathe compared to mammals.
It seems that in the Tawa hallae, the vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small air sacs in its bones.
Since the related lineage of the immense sauropods also had air sacs and a light skeleton, it can be thought that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
As the most primitive known dinosaurs lived in South America, the researchers concluded that the saurians had appeared there.
As a result, the three great lines of evolution split and spread from South America to the rest of the world, i.e. all the emerging lands that formed the supercontinent Pangée.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the team of paleontologists also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to him.
The three species cannot be descended from a common ancestor that would have migrated, the researchers say.
Alan Turner of the New York Museum of Natural History and co-author of the journal Science Studies says there have been at least three waves of migration to North America.
There are, of course, some contradictions.
Martin Sander, a paleontologist in Bonn, says there is an even older species, the Silesaur, that lived in present-day Poland and belongs to a group related to dinosaurs.
According to him, this could give a wrong view because there are a large number of dinosaur fossils in South America that have been preserved while practically none can be found on other continents.
On the other hand, how dinosaurs managed to become the dominant tetrapods of the secondary era when they came from a relatively rare collateral line of the reptile branch, remains a mystery to this day.
At the time of the Triassic, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as present-day crocodile ancestors and many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread throughout the planet, encouraging the development of many new species, while others, who were related to them, disappeared between the Triassic and the Jurassic.
Such a success, however, is not eternal.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There may have been a massive extinction to which the dinosaurs survived in a random way while other reptiles would have disappeared.
