The Worlds of Dreams
Some see, all awake, images and hear voices that no one else can see or hear.
It is not only in the mentally ill, or under the influence of drugs, that the boundaries between imagination and reality are confused.
As long as these phenomena manifest themselves during sleep, everything is fine.
When we lie down in our dark rooms, we can freely indulge in the wildest dreams and fantasies.
However, he who, awake, experiences the dream state, hears and sees things that others do not perceive, quickly has the reputation in our Western world of being mad or drugged, or at least of being an original.
Such images and voices do not appear only in the mentally ill or under the influence of drugs.
It is our imagination that is at stake: it is the same neural activity that allows us to design houses, paint paintings or write novels, but that sometimes incites the boundaries between dream, madness and reality to merge.
A state of conscious awakening, taking the form of a dream, can present itself in the most diverse forms, in the best case this is called visions, at the worst of madness.
But even if the trigger and the effect are different, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiments of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, the second states of the shamans, psychoses and hallucinations are attributable to very similar processes.
There are hallucinations or delusions when the balance, neurotransmitters of the brain - in the first place dopamine, noradrenaline, serotonin and acetylcholine - breaks down and the interaction between different parts of the brain is disrupted.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts are very often manifested during a schizophrenia psychosis.
The force of earthly attraction no longer has power over the person.
Since ancient times, philosophers and doctors have always looked at the relationship between madness and dream.
For Aristotle, hallucinations were a form of dream-awakening; Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, noted in 1861 "a great resemblance between madness and dream", for Sigmund Freud the dream was even "a psychosis with all the irregularities, imaginations, delusions and sensory illusions that compose it".
We are in the fall of 2001 when Henning T turns into a comic book character.
Its body is in two dimensions with sculpted colors.
Earthly attraction no longer has power over him, he hovers at the edge of the ceiling.
He feels a blow.
Behind him are winged, grimacing devil creatures, bloodied mouths, showing teeth.
They chase him, kick him with heavy flamboyant boots, throw him against the walls, he feels pain all over his body.
Loud, nasty voices, screaming, coming out of the walls and the radio.
He can no longer stand those voices that insult and humiliate him.
Henning T. pulls two cables from his stereo chain, makes a loop and attaches it to a hook attached to the ceiling.
He climbs on a baffle and passes the loop around his neck.
He jumps.
The loop is loosening.
Let it serve as a lesson, shout the voices in a choir to rip out the tympanum. "Go to a clinic and get yourself cured!"
Today Henning T. is 40 years old, he has lived six acute psychoses, the last date of 2 years, the first of almost 20 years.
It was triggered by LSD.
The diagnosis: schizo-affective psychosis, paranoid, in addition it is manic-depressive, it takes drugs against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He learned to live with his illness, he has been married for three years.
During the psychosis I experienced terrible fears and deep desperation.
Illusions are a cruel reality.
Approximately one percent of the population suffers at least once in their lifetime from schizophrenia; in psychiatric clinics it is the most common disease after depression.
In a schizophrenia crisis, the people involved can no longer make the difference between the inner world and the outer world, they find themselves in a state of hyper-excitement, which causes them to suffer from hallucinations, megalomania, relationship madness or persecution.
It is very common to hear voices – voices that command, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are not uncommon either.
The person concerned can no longer distinguish between the important and the insignificant, the brain can no longer filter out the disturbing signals, the conscious is drowned under the sensations.
Just like the dream, psychosis opens the locks to a tide of ideas and fantasies from the deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is centered on the subject, according to Professor Thomas Fuchs, head of the department of psychiatry at Heidelberg University Hospital (Allgemeine Psychiatrie im Universit<0xC3><0xA4>tsklinikum).
The schizophrenic is in the center of the situation, all with a meaning centered on him.
At the same time he finds himself in a passive role, he is like in a dream, overcome by events and can not act on them actively.
This is why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled, manipulated.
In general they do not have the opportunity to adjust reality, illusions are a cruel reality, waking up is excluded.
Experience once in your life a hallucination.
Unlike the dream, according to Fuchs, "the sensory and spatial structure of reality that is perceived during psychosis is fundamentally preserved."
Delirious thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of the lived takes place in a real setting.
Why our brain makes these kinds of cabriolets is always a mystery to researchers.
Exceptional situations can cause everyone to momentarily lose their perception of reality, according to Fuchs.
But only a small number of people will develop psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but studies in twins have shown that genes are not the only determining factors.
The researchers assume that the people involved have minimal brain damage.
Neuronal maturation of the brain is thought to be disrupted at an early stage of development, for example by a viral infection of the mother during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
But what remains unexplained is how the neuronal system anomaly occurs and, moreover, the fact that it does not manifest itself for many years.
Environmental factors also play a role – stress or a traumatic experience can be a trigger for psychosis, if there is a predisposition.
Similarly, hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychoses because they act on neurotransmitters.
When our brain heats up.
What is crazy, says psychology professor Erich Kasten of L<0xC3><0xBC>beck, is that psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and take expensive drugs to get rid of them while others buy expensive drugs to get rid of them.
The pleasant or unpleasant perception of illusions is often just a matter of perspective.
Kasten has been compiling reports on hallucinations and illusory image phenomena for the past ten years: last year he published his results in a book entitled "The unreal world in our head".
Hallucinations are many of the concomitant phenomena typical of psychoses but also of an impressive number of other pathologies.
These include mental disorders such as borderline or depression but also migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's disease or head trauma.
It is surprising to note that under certain conditions even the brain of healthy people is prone to hallucinations.
According to Kasten, hallucinations consist of fragments of memories that are normally inhibited.
They take shape when the areas of the brain that process sensory perceptions, are hyperactive or not sufficiently restrained; when our brain heats up but also when there is no stimulation.
Drugs can trigger this condition just like a brain injury or psychosis.
But also the lack of stimuli, stress, the sorrows of love or other exceptional mental states.
In recent studies, one-third of participants admitted to having experienced hallucination at least once in their lives.
