Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children when she was little and often played alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at the age of 13, that the man she called Dad, since she was of thinking age, was not her real father.
These are the same brain areas that are active for visual and acoustic hallucinations, and for real impressions and noises, so it’s very difficult for people like Sarah K to make the difference between illusion and reality.
Hallucinations are also images that form in the brain, which is why they seem so real.”
For Kasten, night dreams are also a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those in acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, the mentally healthy person is able to recognize that fantasies are not real images.
This is why Kasten advises his patients to cherish hallucinations as a special talent.
There is only one step between dreaming and hallucination.
In our world too focused on consciousness we unfortunately quickly tend to take imaginary experiences for pathologies, according to Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and chief physician at the clinic of psychiatry and psychotherapy at Florence Nightingale Hospital in D<0xC3><0xBC>sseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, painful disease but also contains something positive, creative - madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard studied the so-called oniroid form of experience, a particular form of consciousness modification awakened by dream.
Oniroid experiences are very complex semi-dreams that are perceived as real by the one who lives them and that he cannot differentiate from the dream even when he is in a state of awakening.
The oniroid state of consciousness manifests itself during trauma or in situations of extreme pathologies as for patients with polyradiculopathy who are fully conscious, experience motor paralysis.
According to Schmidt-Degenhard, when a human being is threatened by a loss of self and the world, due to a total and lasting inability to move, he replaces this real situation that harms his life, with his own imaginary world that is dissociated from reality.
It is a state of mental boundary between dream and hallucination.
As it is not possible to overcome the situation in reality, a change of world takes place but the real situation is represented in the imagination.
It is, in fact, an intense form of means and interpretation, in a situation in itself intolerable, an organizational capacity that is given to us men, so as not to sink into the void of the loss of consciousness.
Everything is real even later in the memories.
The Zurich-based art historian Peter Cornelius Classen also describes his oneiroid experiences in his book "Change of Heart" as a saving action of the soul.
He is 49 years old, at the time when his conscious part for a journey of several days after the operation of a heart valve followed by a transplant; meanwhile, his body is condemned to remain motionless in resuscitation.
Claussen dives into a world he has created from scratch, visits foreign places, travels back in time. He sees himself as an old man drunk in a railway sanatorium, a robot at his bedside watching over his health.
He lives in the Middle Ages among nobles who manufacture blood-based narcotics.
He is abducted by a Greek biker who takes him to his country, he surfs with his hospital bed in the mists of the Alps and meets a Korean mobster.
It completely absorbs itself into this imaginary world, everything is real even later in its memories.
According to Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
The dream is a completely different state, he writes, describing what he experienced.
Contrary to dreams, memories from mental journeys are extremely clear and very detailed even years later.
One can even say that they are much more distinct and intense than the real experience.
The intensity of this experience shatters the horizon of our other daily experiences, according to psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Ultimately, oniroid delusions, psychoses, hallucinations, and psychedelic experiences show us how fragile our inner representations of external reality are even on standby.
Any change in the state of consciousness, sums up the psychologist Kasten "can cause a deformation of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be quite rewarding.
