75% of working mothers have had work problems because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study “Fecundity and career of women in Spain”, carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey, conducted on 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 years, leaves no room for doubt: 75% of working mothers saw their professional careers limited because of maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences regarding the beginning of life as a couple and the number of children, whether the woman is working or not, and the type of employment she is engaged in.
Those who have no activity outside the home, work part-time or have an unstable job, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier, and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, are delaying the entry into life as a couple and the first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between the ages of 35 and 49 with a fixed job have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after settling in as a couple. This figure rises to 4.1 among those working in the public sector. "These data show that women with a stable job needed more time in their lives to get it, which led them to push back from union and children.
In addition, the type of employment exercised largely influences motherhood, but less the start date of joint life,” explains researcher Margarita Delgado from CSIC.
The level of education is another factor that widens the age gap between women's marriage and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they marry and have their first child later.
The difference also persists among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those who did elementary and higher education were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 years on average, respectively.
"Another distinction also appears between women, depending on their level of education.
While those who have completed elementary studies marry and have their first child before finding a stable job, those who have completed middle or upper-level studies reverse this program and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of a child,” says Ms. Delgado.
